properties.name: Residential Rain Garden
properties.description:
Elmgrove Rain Garden

Two rain gardens capture the whole 800 SF roof area, which once flowed directly into the street. This area of Unincorporated King County's streets have a stormdrain system that flows directly to the Duwamish River.  Built by DIRT Corps in June 2015. DIRT Corps assists adjacent homeowners with ongoing care and maintenance.
properties.title: elmgrove-rain-garden

properties.name: S. Southern St. GreenStreet
properties.description:
Southern Green Street


Four rain gardens capture roadway runoff from the impervious surfaces an keep over 100,000 gallons of water from reaching the Duwamish River each year. Funding provided by grants from King County Wastewater Treatment Division. Built in 2012. DIRT Corps assists adjacent homeowners with ongoing care and maintenance.
properties.title: southern-greenstreet

properties.name: Carleton Grocery Cistern & Rain garden project
properties.description:
Carleton Grocery Rain system

Two cisterns and one rain garden capture roof runoff from the historic store and residence in Georgetown. The project keeps over 50,000 gallons of water from reaching the Duwamish River each year through the combined stormwater and sewer system (CSO).. Funding provided by grants from King County Wastewater Treatment Division, King County Green Grants, and the Duwamish Opportunity Fund. Built in 2016. DIRT Corps assists homeowners with ongoing care and maintenance.
properties.title: carleton-grocery-gsi

properties.name: DIRT Corps warehouse
properties.description:
Dirt Corps Warehouse

DIRT Corps provides skill building and on-the-job training for careers in green infrastructure for young adults 17+. Our crew has been caring for the rain gardens you will see on this tour.  We are accepting applications for Fall & Winter.
properties.title: dirt-corps-warehouse

properties.name: Markey Machinery "Industrial Strength" Bioretention
properties.description:
Markey Machinery "Industrial Strength" Bioretention

Three rain garden cells capture roadway runoff from the impervious surfaces of this industrial business's driveways, and keep over 50,000 gallons of water from reaching the Duwamish River each year. Funding provided by grants from King County Wastewater Treatment Division and Puget Soundkeeper Alliance. Built in 2010.  DIRT Corps assists property owners with ongoing care and maintenance.
properties.title: markey

properties.name: S. Rose GreenStreet
properties.description:
Rose Green Street


Three rain gardens capture nearly 100,000 gallons of roadway runoff from the intersection each year; project also slows traffic and improves walkability of the area without sidewalks. Built with grant funding from the Rose Foundation in 2014. DIRT Corps assists adjacent homeowners with ongoing care and maintenance.
